                <h5>Colour</h5>
                <p>When it comes to diamonds, the colour is graded depending on how white or clear it is. A diamond that is perfectly structured will be completely clear. Sadly, not all colourless diamonds are created equal. They come in a variety of different shades, so a grading scale is used to classify them. The grading scale runs from D to Z. A truly colourless diamond will be rated D, while diamonds that have a noticeable brown or yellow tint are rated Z.</p>
                <h5>Clarity</h5>
                <p>All diamonds, lab-grown and mined, come with inclusions such as uncrystallised carbon, strands of minerals or tiny fractures. These inclusions generally cannot be seen with the naked eye, but they do influence the manner in which a diamond reflects and refracts light. Expert gemmologists will use magnifiers to examine diamonds to understand the number, nature, position and size of the inclusions, as well as their effect on the diamond’s overall appearance. The diamond will then be assigned a clarity grade that ranges from Flawless (F) to Included (I). The scale has 11 grades as follows:</p>
                <p>
                    F – Flawless – Inside and out
                    <br>
                    IF – Internally Flawless – Blemishes on the surface but not internally
                    <br>
                    VVS1 & VVS2 – Very, Very Slightly Included – Two Levels
                    <br>
                    VS1 & VS2 – Very Slightly Included – Two Levels
                    <br>
                    SI1 & SI2 – Slightly Included – Two Levels
                    <br>
                    I1, I2 & I3 – Included – Three Levels
                </p>
                <p>If you’d like to learn more about how diamonds are classified and graded, please feel free to reach out to our diamond experts.</p>
